   {:e #blake3 "a05ac4b1bf50a2fca90c36012ef19878c7cf18a8129bba4a318e83d5c88c7594" :a :db/ident :v :harvest/session-braid-user-1773890429 :op :assert}
   {:e #blake3 "a05ac4b1bf50a2fca90c36012ef19878c7cf18a8129bba4a318e83d5c88c7594" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "DOG-FOOD SESSION 026 — FRICTION ASSESSMENT (in-progress). POSITIVE: (1) braid task create with long titles auto-extracts BACKGROUND/ACCEPTANCE into separate datoms — this is genuinely useful, I can write rich task specs in a single command. (2) braid write assert with -d flag for setting task attributes works well for L2/L3 detail. (3) braid task dep add works reliably for wiring dependency graphs. (4) braid observe captures design insights immediately — the store IS my working memory. (5) The -q flag is essential — without it, the M(t) footer on every command would be overwhelming during bulk task creation. (6) PSR (proactive spec retrieval) surfaced relevant topology specs during task creation — spec IS an active participant. NEGATIVE: (1) Task list truncation is STILL the biggest friction point — I created 27 tasks and cannot verify them via braid task list because titles are invisible. I had to use raw Datalog queries to audit my own tasks. This is the #1 UX priority. (2) braid task set for setting background FAILED silently — I had to discover that write assert -d is the correct path. The command surface is confusing: task set vs write assert for the same entity. (3) No braid task show --short flag — I want to see title + background + acceptance as labeled sections. Currently task show dumps the raw title blob. (4) Harvest warnings are TOO AGGRESSIVE — 44 txns since harvest triggers warnings on every single command. During bulk task creation (27 tasks + 17 deps = 44 txns), every command shows the warning. Need a quiet-during-batch mode or higher threshold. (5) Cannot search tasks by content — no braid task search command. I had to use Datalog queries to find my own tasks.; DATA-MODEL-AS-PROMPT INSIGHT: The schema design for tasks directly shapes agent reasoning quality. Current :task/title holds ALL content in one blob. TASK-DECOMPOSE extracts background/acceptance into separate datoms, but the SCHEMA doesn't enforce this separation. The data model PERMITS the anti-pattern (500-char titles with embedded sections). FROM PROMPT-OPTIMIZATION: constraints restrict, structure navigates. If the data model STRUCTURED tasks as separate attributes from creation time (:task/short-title for L1, :task/description for L2, :task/acceptance for L3), the anti-pattern would be impossible. The schema IS a prompt for task authors — it shapes what they write by what fields are available. Current schema: one :task/title field = one prompt surface = agents write everything there. Better schema: :task/short-title (<=120 chars, required), :task/description (L2, optional), :task/acceptance (L3, optional), :task/files (file paths, optional). The braid task create command would then validate short-title length, rejecting titles >120 chars with a helpful error demonstrating the correct format. This is MAKE ILLEGAL STATES UNREPRESENTABLE (rust-formal-engineering Rule 1) applied to the data model: |task_title| = |valid_short_titles| with no excess cardinality.; Session entity: :task/t-891d2acd; Session entity: :task/t-846524e2; DOG-FOOD SESSION 026 — DEEPER ANALYSIS. The fundamental tension I experience: braid is EXCELLENT for structured knowledge capture (observe, harvest, seed) but POOR for structured knowledge RETRIEVAL during active work. Specifics: (A) CAPTURE is frictionless: braid observe captures an insight in one command. braid task create with rich descriptions works. braid write assert sets arbitrary attributes. The store grows monotonically and nothing is lost. This is the core promise of DDIS working. (B) RETRIEVAL during work is painful: I cannot find my own tasks without Datalog. braid task list truncates. braid task ready shows 271 tasks with no filtering. No full-text search across tasks. No braid task list --grep pattern. No braid task list --created-today. The store has the data but the CLI doesn't surface it efficiently. (C) The BATCH WORKFLOW is unoptimized: Creating 27 tasks required 27 separate braid task create commands, 17 dep add commands, ~15 write assert commands. Each takes ~2 seconds (cargo run overhead). Total: ~2 minutes of pure CLI execution. A braid task create-batch accepting a structured file (YAML/EDN) would be 10x faster. (D) The VERIFICATION WORKFLOW is good: braid query with Datalog lets me audit anything. The store IS the source of truth. I can verify dep edges, check attributes, count results. This is the payoff of C7 (self-bootstrap) — the system can inspect itself. (E) The SEED is genuinely useful: braid seed --task topology showed me relevant spec elements, recent observations, and session history. It IS a compressed knowledge projection. The L0/L1/L2/L3 pyramid would make it even better.; DOG-FOOD INSIGHT: The API-as-prompt principle reveals a HIERARCHY OF PROMPT SURFACES in braid, ordered by frequency of agent interaction and impact on agent reasoning: (1) GUIDANCE FOOTER — injected into EVERY tool response. Highest frequency, lowest token count. This is AMBIENT activation — shapes the trajectory without consuming k*. Currently works well (M(t) + next action). (2) TASK TITLES — read every time agent picks work. High frequency, should be L1 activation patterns. Currently BROKEN (truncated, mixed content). (3) SEED CONTEXT — read once at session start. Medium frequency, highest token count. Currently GOOD (braid seed assembles relevant context). (4) STATUS DASHBOARD — read periodically for orientation. Medium frequency, medium tokens. Currently OK but missing topology. (5) COMMAND OUTPUT — read per invocation. Low frequency per command, high variety. The biggest gap: NOT ALL OUTPUTS USE SPEC-LANGUAGE. Most just dump data. (6) HELP TEXT — read when agent is confused. Lowest frequency, highest impact when invoked. Currently CONSTRAINT-BASED (flag lists), should be DEMONSTRATION-BASED. (7) ERROR MESSAGES — read on failure. Low frequency, CRITICAL impact. Currently MISSING recovery actions for most errors. The OPTIMIZATION ORDER follows from frequency * impact: fix task titles (2) first, then error messages (7), then command output (5), then help text (6), then status (4). Guidance footer (1) and seed (3) are already good.; DOG-FOOD SESSION 026 — OVERALL ASSESSMENT. Score: 7.5/10 (up from 6/10 pre-Session-025, down from 9.5/10 subjective peak). What I LOVE: (1) The store as working memory — every insight persisted, every decision traceable, nothing lost across sessions. This is the fundamental value proposition working. (2) The seed as session bootstrapping — I started this session with full context from prior work. (3) The harvest as session closing — knowledge extraction is automatic and reliable. (4) The spec as active participant — PSR surfaces relevant invariants during task creation. (5) The Datalog query engine — I can ask arbitrary questions about my own project state. What NEEDS WORK: (1) Task management UX is the weakest link. List truncation, no search, no filtering, confusing set vs write-assert boundary. This is the #1 priority because tasks are the PRIMARY interface for agents. (2) Batch operations — creating 27 tasks should be one command, not 27. (3) Harvest warning threshold — during bulk work, every command warns. Need session-aware thresholds. (4) Progressive disclosure — braid status shows everything at L2 always. Should adapt to k* (show L0 late in session, L2 early). (5) Command discoverability — I had to guess that write assert was the way to set task attributes. The error message from task set should suggest the alternative. DEEPEST INSIGHT: The system excels at the DURABLE KNOWLEDGE layer (store, harvest, seed) but needs work on the OPERATIONAL layer (task management, batch ops, search, progressive display). The foundation is sound — the algebra works, the coherence model works, the bilateral loop works. The gap is between mathematical elegance and operational ergonomics.; Session entity: :task/t-8b308e91; Session entity: :task/t-1029e16f; Session entity: :task/t-dbca7795; DESIGN PRINCIPLE: PROMPT SURFACE HIERARCHY for braid. Every agent-facing surface has a frequency, token cost, and activation impact. Optimize in order of frequency*impact: (1) GUIDANCE FOOTER [every response, ~30 tokens, ambient activation] — DONE, works well. (2) TASK TITLES [every task pick, ~80 tokens, routing activation] — BROKEN, needs pyramid display + short-title enforcement. (3) SEED CONTEXT [session start, ~2000 tokens, trajectory seed] — DONE, works well. (4) STATUS DASHBOARD [periodic, ~200 tokens, orientation] — OK, needs topology line. (5) COMMAND OUTPUT [per invocation, ~100-300 tokens, action guidance] — NEEDS demonstration format, spec-language. (6) HELP TEXT [on confusion, ~200 tokens, recovery navigation] — NEEDS demonstration-first format. (7) ERROR MESSAGES [on failure, ~50 tokens, recovery action] — NEEDS spec-language + recovery commands (INV-INTERFACE-009). The priority order for the operational ergonomics EPIC: task titles (2) > error messages (7) > task search/filter > command output (5) > help text (6) > batch ops. This should inform the dependency ordering of our tasks.; Session entity: :task/t-ea2d7a05; Session entity: :task/t-d5ac7417; FORMAL INSIGHT: The task management UX gap IS a coherence gap in the formal framework. Phi_SP (spec-impl boundary divergence) measures gaps between what's specified and what's implemented. But there's an UNSTATED boundary: the Phi_UX between what the SYSTEM KNOWS (store has 278 tasks with rich attributes) and what the AGENT CAN ACCESS (truncated titles, no search, no filtering). This is a new instance of REFLEXIVE DIVERGENCE (spec/22-reflexive.md): the system's CAPABILITY MODEL claims rich task management, but the system's INTERFACE provides only primitive listing. The store IS the source of truth — but truth locked behind Datalog queries is truth that agents cannot easily access. FORMALLY: Let U(S) be the usable information from store S via the CLI interface. Let T(S) be the total information in S. The USABILITY RATIO u(S) = |U(S)| / |T(S)| should approach 1.0 as the interface matures. Currently u(S) for task management is approximately 0.3 — agents can access ~30% of task information without raw queries. Fixing task display (pyramid), search, and filtering pushes u(S) toward 0.8+. This is the operational analogue of the bilateral forward scan: does the interface satisfy the specification?" :op :assert}
